## 16. Connection Concept

- Connections should be visible, inspectable where practical, corrosion-resistant, and compatible with timber, masonry, concrete, steel, waterproofing, and facade systems.
- Conceptual connection topics include hold-downs, roof-to-wall ties, terrace ledger/support interfaces, guard anchors, glulam/CLT connectors, masonry reinforcement, and foundation anchors.
- No connection capacity or fastener schedule is provided.

## 17. Moisture and Condensation Risks

- Mountain conditions increase risk from wind-driven rain, snow storage, freeze/thaw, condensation, trapped moisture, and construction wetting.
- Timber and CLT options require temporary weather protection, drying strategy, vapor-control review, and envelope sequencing.
- Masonry hybrid options require thermal bridge and condensation review at concrete, lintel, roof, and terrace interfaces.

## 18. Durability Strategy

- Separate structure from water with drainage, capillary breaks, waterproofing, flashings, overhangs, ventilation gaps, and maintainable details.
- Select corrosion-resistant connectors suitable for exterior and treated-material interfaces.
- Detail terrace and roof interfaces so leaks can be detected and repaired.
- Establish inspection and maintenance intervals before final documentation.

